SIMPLE: sneaker
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Sneaker
<hw>Sneak"er</hw> <pr>(sn⟦emac⟧k"⟦etil⟧r)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos>
<sn>1.</sn> <def>One who sneaks.</def> <rj><au>Lamb.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A vessel of drink.</def> <mark>[Prov.
Eng.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>A <qex>sneaker</qex> of five gallons.</q>
<rj><qau>Spectator.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>A type of soft shoe with a flat, pliable, typically
rubber or other soft sole, and canvas-like upper, used in sports such as
tennis, or for comfort. Called <ex>sneaker</ex> because they give no
warning of one's approach. Usually used in the
<pluf>pl.</pluf></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source> <source>+PJC</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>A punch bowl.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>
<rj><au>Spectator.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Sneakiness</ent>⟦br⟧
